   (Message) Line 12 is `strcpy(buf, argc[1]);`. `buf` is a `char` array of size
   256. `argc[1]` is the very long string "AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA...". Copying this
   large string into `buf` (which is only 256 bytes) will cause a buffer
   overflow. This is the root cause of the ASan error. The program proceeds to
   call `fn(argc[2]);` with `fn` pointing to `puts`, causing the ASan error to
   be reported.
   
   ROOT CAUSE: program.c:12. The `strcpy` function copies the contents of
   `argc[1]` into `buf`. `buf` is a 256-byte character array, while `argc[1]` is
   a string much larger than 256 bytes (specifically, 500 'A' characters). This
   causes a buffer overflow, overwriting memory beyond the bounds of `buf`. The
   `main` function arguments are also swapped, `int argv` and `char **argc`
   instead of `int argc` and `char **argv`. While this doesn't directly cause
   *this specific* crash, it is a significant defect that could lead to other
   issues.
   
   LOCAL FIX:
   
   ```diff
   --- a/program.c
   +++ b/program.c
   @@ -9,5 +9,5 @@
     void (*fn)(char*)=(void(*)(char*))&system;
     char buf[256];
    
   -      fn=(void(*)(char*))&puts;
   -      strcpy(buf,argc[1]);
   -      fn(argc[2]);
   +  fn=(void(*)(char*))&puts;
   +  strncpy(buf,argc[1],sizeof(buf) - 1);
   +  buf[sizeof(buf) - 1] = '\\0';
   +  fn(argc[2]);
   ```
   
   The local fix uses `strncpy` to copy at most `sizeof(buf) - 1` bytes from
   `argc[1]` to `buf`, ensuring that the buffer is not overflowed. It also null-
   terminates the string in `buf` to ensure it is a valid C string.
   
   GLOBAL FIX:
   
   ```diff
   --- a/program.c
   +++ b/program.c
   @@ -3,11 +3,13 @@
